<doc id="335186" wikidata="Q2713798" url="?curid=335186" title="Delma">
<text>Delma is a genus of lizards in the family Pygopodidae. The genus &quot;Delma&quot; contains 22 valid described species, all of which are endemic to Australia.

==Species==
Recognized species of &quot;Delma&quot; according to the Reptile Database:
*&quot;Delma australis&quot; – marble-faced delma
*&quot;Delma borea&quot; – rusty-topped delma
*&quot;Delma butleri&quot; – Butler&#x27;s legless lizard, Butler&#x27;s scalyfoot, spinifex snake-lizard, unbanded delma
*&quot;Delma concinna&quot; – javelin lizard
*&quot;Delma desmosa&quot; – desert delma
*&quot;Delma elegans&quot; – Pilbara delma
*&quot;Delma fraseri&quot; – Fraser&#x27;s delma, Fraser&#x27;s scalyfoot
*&quot;Delma grayii&quot; – side-barred delma, Gray&#x27;s legless lizard
*&quot;Delma hebesa&quot; – heath delma
*&quot;Delma impar&quot; – striped legless lizard
*&quot;Delma inornata&quot; – patternless delma, olive legless lizard, olive snake-lizard
*&quot;Delma labialis&quot; – striped-tailed delma, single-striped delma
*&quot;Delma mitella&quot; – Atherton delma
*&quot;Delma molleri&quot; – Gulfs delma, Adelaide delma
*&quot;Delma nasuta&quot; – sharp-snouted delma, sharp-snouted legless lizard
*&quot;Delma pax&quot; – peace delma
*&quot;Delma petersoni&quot; – painted delma
*&quot;Delma plebeia&quot; – leaden delma
*&quot;Delma tealei&quot; – North West Cape delma, Teale&#x27;s delma
*&quot;Delma tincta&quot; – excitable delma
*&quot;Delma torquata&quot; – collared delma, adorned delma
*&quot;Delma vescolineata&quot; - Hunter Valley delma

&quot;Nota bene&quot;: A binomial authority in parentheses indicates that the species was originally described in a genus other than &quot;Delma&quot;.

==References==
==Further reading==
*Boulenger GA (1885). &quot;Catalogue of the Lizards in the British Museum (Natural History). Second Edition. Volume I. ... Pygopodidæ ...&quot; London: Trustees of the British Museum (Natural History). (Taylor and Francis, printers). xii + 436 pp. + Plates I-XXXII. (Genus &quot;Delma&quot;, p. 243).
*Gray JE (1831). &quot;Description of a new Genus of Ophisaurean Animal, discovered by the late James Hunter, Esq., in New Holland&quot;. &quot;Zoological Miscellany&quot; 1:14. (&quot;Delma&quot;, new genus).</text><links>
